> "The climate of our culture is changing. Under these new rains, new suns, small things grow great, and what was great grows small; whole species disappear and are replaced." --[Randall Jarrell](!Wikipedia)^["A Sad Heart at the Supermarket", _Daedalus_, vol. 89, no. 2 (Spring 1960)]

The [Amazon Kindle](!Wikipedia) has ignited the [ebook](!Wikipedia) market by providing a [e-ink](!Wikipedia) interface which is visually competitive with paper, and easy access to a remarkable fraction of Amazon's inventory. It's very nice.

The pricing of the ebooks has caused some controversy; why should an ebook cost as much as $3/4$ or more than the book? The Kindle's ebooks are just small files being downloaded over a cellular network, as opposed to a multi-pound slab of exactingly manufactured wood and cloth. The former is created and delivered instantly, while the latter requires elaborate factories and transport to get into the reader's hands. Surely there is vast overhead for the paper, and the ebook's prices should reflect the fact that once created, the marginal cost of another copy is close to 0¢.

Not many expect ebooks to be priced in cents, since the author expects to be paid a fair bit for her writing, and the publisher expects to be paid for editing & formatting it, and Amazon is there discreetly coughing for its (substantial) share of the transactions[^scratch]. So it won't be 0¢, but why not $3 or less?

# The price is not right

In a sense, this is a [very easy](!Wikipedia "Law of supply and demand") question. The right price for ebooks is whatever the market will bear. If $3 is not the right price, then consumers will not buy, and the price will continue to fall until they do.

In another sense, it's a difficult question as some people seem to be thinking in medieval terms, of the '[just price](!Wikipedia)', which has no objective meaning & so cannot be definitively set[^just].

## Subsidies

The more interesting question is, is there a price level mutually acceptable to consumers & sellers of books which permit the latter to survive in their current corporate forms? If there isn't, *should* the latter survive? That is: if books are not economically sustainable at prices below $3, say, will society be worse off? Should publishers or novelists be subsidized[^subsidy]?

The more I think about it, the harder I find justifying any subsidy.

We value high author royalties because this allows authors to specialize in being authors; specialization is a good thing because it allows authors to produce more than they otherwise would; and higher production is good because we value the fruits thereof.

But higher production isn't always good; production can be misguided or wasted ^[cf. [broken window fallacy](!Wikipedia)].

# 100 apples in the barrel

> "Where words are scarce, they are seldom spent in vain,\
> For they breathe truth that breathe their words in pain." --William Shakespeare^[[_King Richard II_](!Wikipedia "Richard II (play)")]  

Here's an analogy. Suppose we all have 100 apples. Our lives do not revolve around apples, though we like them well enough. But still, 100 is too many; even if we ate 5 a day, the rest would go bad before we ate them. And of course, it's unlikely that any of us will go to the greengrocers and buy *more*. The [marginal utility](!Wikipedia) of apples for us have plunged to zero^[Or below; I dislike clutter.].

From our perspective, the farmer bringing a truck of apples to the greengrocers has wasted his labor. Let's hope he'll find *something* to do with those surplus apples so the resources that went into making them were not wasted - maybe bake some apple pies, or compost them all.

Now suppose this wasn't a one-time gift. We live in a magic world where everyone gets 100 apples a week. Now it isn't one trip that was useless, it's the farmer's entire career. Isn't he wasting his life? He's a smart fellow - no reason he couldn't go do something more useful.

Sure, we can invent ways to employ this farmer. Perhaps every week he breaks into everybody's kitchens and steals their apples so they have to buy apples from him. Perhaps he'll run a large marketing campaign to convince everyone that his apples are somehow superior to the magical apples. Perhaps some people get [Granny Smith](!Wikipedia)s but really wanted [Red Delicious](!Wikipedia)es, and he makes himself an apple-trading hub, filling in deficits with apples he grows. Perhaps he lives on government subsidy checks & farms apples as a hobby. Or something.

But nevertheless, these apple-farmers represent a [dead-weight loss](!Wikipedia). That's bad.

# 100 books on the shelf

> "Do technology and economic growth create problems? Certainly. But as Maurice Chevalier said about the disadvantages of growing old, consider the alternative.\
