Now, can we apply this analogy? I don't have 100 apples, but perhaps I have - 100 novels.

Not random novels, but [science fiction](!Wikipedia) novels. And not just any 100 Sci-Fi novels, but the elite, the select, the critically acclaimed winners of the 2 most prestigious SF awards for the last 50 years^[I realize that double-winners mean the equation isn't simply $2 \times 50$, but close enough.]: the [Hugo](!Wikipedia "Hugo Award") and [Nebula Award](!Wikipedia)s.

## Reading them


> "Time destroys the groundless conceits of men; it confirms decisions founded on reality." --[Cicero](!Wikipedia)^[_De Natura Deorum_, Bk II.2]

Suppose I read industriously at the rate of 1 a week[^rate], or 52 a year. I will finish this 100 in ~2 years.

Think about that. 2 years. It will take an appreciable fraction of my life just to read a vanishingly small fraction of one small fiction genre, that itself has existed for less than 2 centuries and been written almost exclusively in 2 countries[^geo].

And what if I want to read the prequels and sequels? Not all winners are as prolific in sequels & prequels as _[Dune](!Wikipedia "Dune universe")_, but these winners include many duologies and trilogies (or more)[^sequels]. I can probably expect to lose another 2 or 6 years to them. Certainly, I can expect it to take another 4 years to read the 2 top runner-ups for each award. And did I mention that these awards have multiple categories? Many of SF's greatest works are short stories or novellas, which compete for different Nebula & Hugo awards.

And of course, it's not like the Hugo & Nebula awards are the definitive list of SF 'books to read' - _[The Encyclopedia of Science Fiction](!Wikipedia)_ treats of hundreds of writers, and mentions thousands of works; _[The Encyclopedia of Fantasy](!Wikipedia)_ has >4000 entries. Like a fractal coast, my reading list becomes longer the more thoroughly I search...

## New = bad

> "It is worth serious consideration how great an amount of time -- their own and other people's -- and of paper is wasted by this swarm of mediocre poets, and how injurious their influence is. For the public always seizes on what is new, and shows even more inclination to what is perverse and dull, as being akin to its own nature. These works of the mediocre, therefore, draw the public away and hold it back from genuine masterpieces, and from the education they afford. Thus they work directly against the benign influence of genius, ruin taste more and more, and so arrest the progress of the age." --[Arthur Schopenhauer](!Wikipedia)^[_[The World as Will and Representation](!Wikipedia)_, section 51, footnote 41]

So I'm a decade into my SF reading quest; if the SF industry had imploded the day I started, I still will neither know nor care.

I would be better off, actually, if the industry *did* implode! The last SF or Fantasy I read was [Brandon Sanderson](!Wikipedia)'s _[Mistborn](!Wikipedia "Mistborn series")_ trilogy. It was pretty good, but I know I could've done much better. My reading time is finite, and reading _Mistborn_ pushed out reading [Gene Wolfe](!Wikipedia)'s _[Book of the Long Sun](!Wikipedia)_ tetralogy - which I ultimately enjoyed more. If the industry had imploded before _Mistborn_ was published, I would've read _Long Sun_ instead.

(The connection to other aspects of modern life and _[akrasia](!Wikipedia)_ is apparent: there's a [Gresham's Law](!Wikipedia) whereby cheap yet unsatisfying works will push out more satisfying but more demanding entertainment.)

It wouldn't be difficult to spend the rest of my life reading only SF published before 2009, and it would be more efficient as time is better than I at winnowing the good from the bad.

### Generalizing this

But only reading SF is impoverishing. I always wanted to get into mysteries and French literature. But there go another 2 decades, at least. Now I'm in my 50s. I'd better get cracking if I ever want to go through English literature or Asian, or maybe any nonfiction!

So, why do I care what happens to the SF market? How does it concern me that the short story magazines (which incubate new writers) are collapsing? I have no need for them. I already have 100 apples.

### Music

Or how about music? Just the genre of classical music. I once downloaded a complete collection of [J.S. Bach](!Wikipedia) which came to 17 gigabytes. I've no idea how many hours of music that is, and am too frightened to calculate it. And how many listens would it take to reasonably appreciate it? A lifetime, perhaps. Why should I care about some publisher trying to record another CD of the [Brandenburg Concertos](!Wikipedia)? I'm not a conductor, I will hear no improvement. To me, there is no difference between the world's greatest violinist and the 10^th^-greatest.

### Movies

Or consider another medium: movies. Have you seen even a fraction of the [IMDB](!Wikipedia "Internet Movie Database")'s [Top 250](http://www.imdb.com/chart/top)? There are some pretty incredible movies in there. Some of them are profound, others moving, and not a few profoundly moving. Why are you going to watch _[Transformers 2](!Wikipedia "Transformers: Revenge of the Fallen")_ or _[Ice Age 3](!Wikipedia "Ice Age: Dawn of the Dinosaurs")_? For entertainment value? But there are movies in that list which are far more entertaining, I assure you.

Even if you've seen the top 50, there's another 200 to choose from. (As before, at 1 or 2 a week, there's years worth there.) If you think the IMDB is too faddish and Internet-centric, there's no shortage of other lists - the _New York Times_ would be happy to tell you all about ["The Best 1,000 Movies Ever Made"](http://www.nytimes.com/ref/movies/1000best.html) (20 years), for example. And what about television?

### Genres in general

Basically, any field over a century old has built up a sufficient stock of masterpieces for these arguments to work.

Fields that are new, or still technically developing, may be able to evade these arguments. For example, video games - even the greatest arcade games from 20 or 30 years ago have a hard time competing against even average games from within the past few years.

But even new genres have problems with this argument. After all, while we may not be able to put artworks into neat countable categories of 'painting' or 'Russian novel', there is something we *can* count and which is absolutely crucial to the argument: time. Our lives are only so long, and they are denominated quite precisely, nanosecond by nanosecond. We only live 500,000 waking hours^[$\text{total hours} - \text{sleeping hours}$, or, $80 \text{years} \times 365 \text{days} \times 24 \text{hours} = 700800$; $700800 - (\frac{1}{3} \times 700800) = 467200$].

Does it matter whether it's a ballet or a novel if we spend 1 of those hours interacting with or collaborating with it? The art's 'essence' or 'artness' may be as non-commodified as we please, but we can't get around the limits on ourselves. For our finite lives, it's good enough if we call it art. And we don't necessarily need to assume substitution of works *across* genres; given enough time, any genre you please will outrun your lifespan.

